TypeScript won&#39;t [infer a user-defined type guard](https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/16069) for you.  You have to annotate it yourself, like this:

    const makeIsBox = &lt;L extends Letter&gt;(fn: (letter: Letter) =&gt; letter is L) =&gt; (
      box: Box
    ): box is Extract&lt;Box, { type: L }&gt; =&gt; fn(box.type);

This still only needs to be generic in `L`.  It takes a function of type `(l: Letter)=&gt;l is L` and returns a function of type `(b: Box)=&gt;b is Extract&lt;Box, {type: L}&gt;`.  That&#39;s using the [`Extract` utility type](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/utility-types.html#extracttu) to select just the member of the `Box` union which is assignable to `{type: L}`. 

It should work the way you want:
    
    const isBoxA = makeIsBox(isA);
    
    declare const box: Box;
   
    if (isBoxA(box)) {
      const value = box.value;
    } else {
      const status = box.status;
    }

